text: Just imagine, there might have been people sitting at the first recital of Beowulf complaining about how derivative of The Odyssey it is with it's heroes and monsters and the author's inability to create something new. And those people would be just as stupid as those demanding "the new" today because they would be overlooking the fact that everything any man or woman does is built upon what others did first. No one who goes to the theater thinks "King Lear? Again?" because it doesn't matter how often a story is told only how well it is told. Remake, remix, rearrange, revise, retell. All viable forms of expression that are just as valid as the original works that inspired the artist to recreate it in their own words/vision/way. Nostalgia is never your friend.

text: This movie looks like it is going to suck, in comparison to the original. The whole point was the motivation of the "bad guys" and Bodhi, contrasted to Utah's "good guy" rules and regulations, in the backdrop of the surfing/skating  "anti establishment" "carefree" culture that existed in those sports, during that time in history. This one looks like extended stunt sequences for a new audience that gets its thrills predominantly from video games. It's probably going to bomb. Hard.   Folks who remember the original will be disappointed, and the newbies who don't, won't get it, will compare it to the Fast & Furious franchises, and if enough of them come to see it, will quickly forget it.  Watch the original instead.

This is a complete miss, imho.

text: So why are they even calling this movie Point Break if only 6 seconds of this 2 and 1/2 minute trailer is related at all to surfing?  That's like if you made Silence of the Lambs but nowhere in the plot was Starling's backstory.  At this point it might make more sense for them to just call this Fast and the Furious 8 seeing as that might make them more money and less people angry and it's the same director as the first one.  Two favourite films of mine got remade by hollywood this year in a nostalgia cash grab.  First it was Poltergeist, then it was Point Break.  Even though looking back they both have their flaws, they both had at least charm and style that kept people coming back and inspired future filmmakers to make motion pictures.  The reason the new Poltergeist did not work was because all of the things it was copying from the original many modern horror films have done to death.  This is the reason this has a slim chance of being good. Films like Fast and the Furious have used up the formula so many times it is completely pointless to remake it.  Hopefully this remake and all of the other ones that everybody hates will be forgotten with time and the new, original, groundbreaking ideas will live on and be cherished.  That's the thing with bad remakes, they eventually just go away, and if you ask most people growing up today they will say they like the original Willy Wonka to the Burton remake and most will have no clue that Psycho was ever remade by the guy who did Good Will Hunting.  Sure it's a pain to see an action film everyone seemed to love remade for money, but in time the memory of it will fade and future generation won't even know this was a thing.  Also why does it look like Utah is smiling or at the least not looking phased by anything when he says his last line in the trailer???  I mean Reaves was not by any means the best actor, but he at least looked serious when the scene was supposed to be serious like the scene where he shoots his gun into the air instead of shooing Bodhi.  If something that basic is off the movie is heading towards a future of dollar bins in grocery stores across the world.

But everything changed once I hit 1:20. I thought to myself, this looks oddly familiar. As I watched the trailer further I had to pause at about 2:16 to turn towards my TV and searched for the remote to turn down the volume because it was distracting. When I finally found my remote, I aimed it at the TV and paused for a second right before hitting that mute button. I saw Paul Walker in a confrontation with Vin Diesel who was telling Paul to "Move his car." and "Brian you're a cop!" Without resuming play on Youtube, I looked at the video, looked at the TV, looked at the video, looked at the TV, looked at the video, and said, "Those assholes."

text: How could someone take one of the best, most original movies ever made (Point Break- 1991), and Reboot it into one of the absolute *_worst_* movies ever made?  How does that even happen? I think we can all agree that almost all remakes and reboots that have been made in the past decade have just been flat-out *_terrible_* aside from a very select few such as Rob Zombie's 'Halloween' (2007), Michael Bay's 'The Texas Chainsaw Massacre' (2003), and of course, one of my personal favorites, the *_I Spit On Your Grave Trilogy_* even though i believe that only the first one is a remake. All 3 were pretty damn good. The 3rd one is different and not what you'd expect, but really good.
